--- Réponse Brut du LLM ---
 from scipy import signal
   result = signal.correlate(a, b, mode='same')
</code>
END SOLUTION
The 'mode' parameter of the correlate function allows for different types of correlation. The 'same' option returns an output that is the same size as a, with zero-padding at the edges. If you want to perform circular cross-correlation, you can use the 'valid' mode and then manually wrap around the array:
<code>
   result = np.concatenate((signal.correlate(a, b, mode='valid'), signal.correlate(a, b, mode='valid')[:len(b)-1]))
</code>
This will give you a result that is the same size as b, with circular correlation applied.
